      "date": "2012-10-10 16:14:57.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\nI don't understand why there is a need to fall back to RR if the QOS allocation ran out of OSTs?  The OSTs are not going to be more available with RR allocation, or is the RR code trying harder to wait for OSTs to recover?  With the old code if there were at least 3/4 of the requests stripes that could be allocated then it succeeded and continues on. If not, then an error was returned to the caller. This was of course only the case after having waited for all OSTs to complete precreation if they were currently out of objects, but not if they are out of space or offline. \n\nPlease don't name tests test_116() and test_116a(), since it is then impossible to run just test_116(). Instead, rename the old test to 116a and the new one 116b, with a comment that the old test used to be named 116 (\"# was named test_116\")..",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "246ec8a90b32e8e6fb46e6ee80b5e2ae7f384c13",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 119,
        "name": "Alex Zhuravlev",
        "email": "bzzz@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "bzzz"
      },
      "date": "2012-10-10 20:06:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nplease look at lov's alloc_qos():\n\n         if (good_osts < stripe_cnt_min)\n                GOTO(out, rc = -EAGAIN);\n\nthen:\n\n        if (rc == -EAGAIN)\n                rc = alloc_rr(lov, idx_arr, stripe_cnt, poolname, flags);\n\n\nI tend to agree with the argument, but what about LOV code above?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "590314502ad001ddd3b03b9c02247df0bbc85824",
